				</div>

			</div>
			<p>
				You can drag the arrows to explore how the values change for each comparison teqnique.
			</p>
			<div class="card">
				<div id="MhDistance" style="display:none">
					<h3>Manhattan Distance</h3>
					<b>Manhattan Distance</b> is a computationally cheap way to compare vectors.
					It is calculated as the sum of the absolute differences between the corresponding elements of two
					vectors:

					$$|x_1 - x_2| + |y_1 - y_2| + \dots + |n_1 - n_2|$$
				</div>

				<div id="EcDistance" style="display:none">
					<h3>Euclidean Distance</h3>
					<b>Euclidean Distance</b> is a more precise comparison than Manhattan distance, but it is also more
					computationally expensive.
					It measures the straight-line distance between two points in space:

					$$\sqrt{(x_1 - x_2)^2 + (y_1 - y_2)^2 + \dots + (n_1 - n_2)^2}$$
				</div>

				<div id="DotProduct" style="display:none">
					<h3>Dot Product</h3>
					The <b>Dot Product</b> of two vectors returns the product of their magnitudes and the cosine of the
					angle between them:
					<br>
					Keep in mind that the value you see is not the angle but the cosine of the angel. And cos(180) = -1 and cos(0) = 1
					that is why you will see that when the arrows overlap you get 1 x length and when the arrows are opposite each other you get -1 x lenght

					$$A \cdot B = \|A\| \|B\| \cos(\theta)$$

					This can be expanded to

					$$A \cdot B = x_1x_2 + y_1y_2 + \dots + n_1n_2$$

					The value can range from $$-\infty | \infty$$.
				</div>

				<div id="CosineSimilarity" style="display:none">
					<h3>Cosine Similarity</h3>
					<b>Cosine Similarity</b> is a normalized form of the dot product.
					It measures the cosine of the angle between two vectors, ignoring their magnitudes:

					$$\cos(\theta) = \frac{A \cdot B}{\|A\|\|B\|}$$

					The result ranges from -1 (opposite direction) to 1 (same direction).
				</div>

			</div>
		</div>
	</div>
</div>
